Path-dependent types — briefly.

Types can be members of values, not just members of classes. When a type is nested inside another type, the inner type belongs to a particular instance of the outer one — and the resulting type is called a path-dependent type, because its full name includes the specific value it lives on.

Picture an outer class that contains an inner class, and two separate instances of the outer. Each instance has its own version of the inner type. A value built from the first instance's inner type fits where that exact instance's inner type is expected, but it does not fit where the second instance's inner type is expected — even though the inner class is written once, the two instances' inner types are distinct. The path to the type — through this particular outer value — is part of its identity.

This is exotic, but real. Spark's typed dataset exploits path-dependent types in places to keep certain values tied to the context that produced them. It is mentioned here purely for recognition — you will almost never write a path-dependent type yourself, but when you see a type whose name runs through a value, this is what is going on.
